<li id="cite_note-Azuma-1990-37"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Azuma-1990_37-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Azuma-1990_37-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFAzuma1990" class="citation book cs1">Azuma, Shoji (1990). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=w5tVDKFqZscC&amp;pg=PA193">"Word Order vs. Word Class: Portmanteau Sentences in Bilinguals"</a>. In Hoji, Hajime; Clancy, Patricia (eds.). <i>Japanese/Korean Linguistics: Volume 2</i>. Center for the Study of Language (CSLI). <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-881526-14-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-881526-14-8"><bdi>978-1-881526-14-8</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Word+Order+vs.+Word+Class%3A+Portmanteau+Sentences+in+Bilinguals&amp;rft.btitle=Japanese%2FKorean+Linguistics%3A+Volume+2&amp;rft.pub=Center+for+the+Study+of+Language+%28CSLI%29&amp;rft.date=1990&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-881526-14-8&amp;rft.aulast=Azuma&amp;rft.aufirst=Shoji&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dw5tVDKFqZscC%26pg%3DPA193&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACode-switching" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Chan-2015-38"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Chan-2015_38-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFChan2015" class="citation journal cs1">Chan, Brian Hok-Shing (21 December 2015). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4685654">"Portmanteau Constructions, Phrase Structure, and Linearization"</a>. <i>Frontiers in Psychology</i>. <b>6</b>: 1851. <a href="/wiki/Doi_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="Doi (identifier)">doi</a>:<span class="id-lock-free" title="Freely accessible"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://doi.org/10.3389%2Ffpsyg.2015.01851">10.3389/fpsyg.2015.01851</a></span>. <a href="/wiki/ISSN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISSN (identifier)">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/issn/1664-1078">1664-1078</a>. <a href="/wiki/PMC_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="PMC (identifier)">PMC</a>&#160;<span class="id-lock-free" title="Freely accessible"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4685654">4685654</a></span>. <a href="/wiki/PMID_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="PMID (identifier)">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26733894">26733894</a>. <q>The term "portmanteau" is supposed to refer to "blends" originally (e.g., "smog" that is blended from "smoke" and "fog"). Portmanteau constructions in code-switching obviously do not refer to such lexical blends but they are more like "syntactic blends" (e.g., SVOV is blended from SVO and SOV).</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Frontiers+in+Psychology&amp;rft.atitle=Portmanteau+Constructions%2C+Phrase+Structure%2C+and+Linearization&amp;rft.volume=6&amp;rft.pages=1851&amp;rft.date=2015-12-21&amp;rft_id=http